A Republican Strategy to Hinder Obama's Reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from a lightning strike.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the vote, and strip citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law.
For this reason, the Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to keep in mind that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo identification document issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity document.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that usually vote for the Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, in 2011, Republican legislators supported certain laws that abolished the registration of voters on the same day of the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 led to a fall in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favored reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter represented no more than 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same thing happened.
These represent no more than 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
