The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a shock last summer, and with good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What's more, it's the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or “least bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But it's not entirely clear to physicists that this is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at an important physics conference held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data are still needed to be completely sure.
In any case, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of making mistakes seem small. We'll see what it's all about.
There is, in this big world, a generalized and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been demonstrated that there is also such a law in it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same “quantum state”; a “state” that consists, roughly speaking, of some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find good citizens called Fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other hand, there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories website The Particle Adventure, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and “force particles”, through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the “particle of light” that acts as a “messenger” of the electromagnetic force.
In effect, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorders” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this “disorder” an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing other than a photon; that is, one of the “force-carrying” bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be “disordered” for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energies, a bit as if it were an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
That's why we need an immense particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the large hadron collider is a ring 27 km in circumference!) to achieve such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others don't: a piece of paper, for example, will never remain glued to a refrigerator door by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (such as the photon, by the way), do not.
But what can all these investigations “contribute”? , asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and the predictions of the MS.
For their part, many fervently want them to be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a “new physics” that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, such as that it does not propose any explanation related to gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our daily lives are difficult to predict, but we don't think we're wrong to say that it won't have any.
Just so you can see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories had absolutely no suspicion of the revolution that their work would provoke.
They glimpsed scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, has already said, at first the laser was more of a “laboratory device”.
Just imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research in optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as an “eye” for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That doesn't mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know...
Palliative care. The Best Way to Die... | Le Devoir
In its Dying in Dignity Commission, Quebec recently discussed the sensitive question of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon while a bill is being prepared.
However, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in La Montégie.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year break.
“They had given me five years to live, but I've been like this for seven,” he says, pausing, lying on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this,” he continues.
The disease has taken its toll on him: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts that they help him eat.
Courageous, he even smiles, talks to strangers who give him attention, bring him medicines and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to have my diarrhea cured, it's humiliating,” she confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for that disease.
“In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois Center.
Returning to their childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the big moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses that surround them no longer offer “curative” care.
The biggest fear of Mrs. A., 89, is to die “conscious and drowned”.
But the disease has made her children discover it.
“I have good children,” he adds.
“I have no more desires left in this life,” she says, before accepting that a mask be put on to help her breathe.
And he expects, in the next few days, a final visit from his son who lives in Italy.
Victor-Gadbois offers, with a group of volunteers, body care and nutrition assistance.
It's palliative care given to them when nothing else can be done.
To help make your death more comfortable.
In Quebec, we have one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the center's doctors.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, depending on the demand.
Diabetics no longer have their sugar levels under control.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, who died during the night.
This morning, his son ran out of beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help both patients and their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois Center, the days go by without ever being the same.
Next to a 94-year-old man enjoying his last family reunion in the courtyard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old boy dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two children, after having tried everything to survive.
“For six months now, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under 45 with cancer,” Dr. Christiane Martel worries.
53% of the patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of their life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a care center.
And several agencies, such as the Victor-Gadbois Center and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize almost exclusively in caring for patients with cancer.
It is precisely this great relative lack of health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law that regulates euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminences in palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec healthcare system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone has the right to quality palliative care before they agree to proceed with euthanasia.
“Recently,” she says, “I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room suffering great pain without what was necessary to alleviate her.
I fear that patients want to die just because they don't get the right care.”
And at the same time, many oncologists are stubborn with their patients until the last day, despite the worst forecasts.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already low when she left an exhausting chemotherapy treatment.
“When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me that she was very sorry that I wanted to stop fighting,” he says.
“However, she had told me that there was nothing more to do!”
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been relieved thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care at Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to put the patient to sleep until the time of death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend that we don't understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the disease that has not been alleviated will have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved all say the same thing: “I want to die.”
But that doesn't necessarily mean “I want euthanasia”, but “I want to be relieved”.
