In it, bitcoin was described as “the most successful virtual currency”, “that competes with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as “credits”, used to advance in a video game and that can be earned playing or can be purchased (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously ledger repositories, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are recorded in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This involves solving a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file shredding, that is, of transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical fingerprint.
The computers “take” the new transaction and add a number before “chopping” the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular fingerprint (plus zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is regularly split in two, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
Network life already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
“The flaw used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Major players such as Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that close to 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the “giant sales” were launched.
“$30,000 was exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as well as in the transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are thus cheaper.
The bearer also manages their identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a telephone can “photograph and recognize”, says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to review hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to prevail, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, should this currency be successful.
