A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing for President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever when it comes to the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives him full powers, he decided to play everything for everything.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given that Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial embezzlements.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delusion” and continues to “betray his word” and “trample on the law”.
On the part of his supporters, he assures that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organized in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks haVOC throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: “either they vote on my text or I maintain full powers”, powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt that they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted on were unanimously voted on.
The commentators are amused, on the other hand, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at prayer time, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent Assembly clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all eyes, is finally identical to that of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law”.
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that “the principles” could be replaced by “the rules”, which would have allowed for a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their good will and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider that it is nothing more than a publicity ruse.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with Sharia laws.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “the people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy”.
Liberals' fears are also increased by the fact that the next president of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution, we are within the framework of civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity surrounding article 220, since the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
“We refer specifically to the term qih [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could arise in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule above all of this.”
Beyond its religious nature, the text voted on yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to what they were under the previous regime.
Another sticking point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the Defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by associations for the defense of human rights.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy continues and, henceforth, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to appear on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
“AIF” identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Reverence in the Holy Land
The Jordan River where Jesus was baptized is well worth a visit.
It is believed that anyone who enters this “baptismal font” will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, the easing of the storm and the full nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are found in Jerusalem.
Believers here walk the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin “Via Dolorosa”).
It begins at the Fortress of Anthony, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, it goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of the Anointing and to the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place there is also the Christian navel, symbolic of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the site where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for Jews, the Western Wall; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will later come true.
Take a vertical trip
The ruins of Fortress Masada were what was left of a secret refuge against enemies, which Herod the Great ordered to be built in 25 BC. C. for your family.
They are found on mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are dedicated to climbing can get there by their own means.
Others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous Hermón ski resort, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
There, bus services are available from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly inhabited at the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
In a single trip you won't be able to visit them all.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth visiting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It contains the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological pieces.
The Art Museum in Tel Aviv is worth a visit.
His exhibition of paintings includes canvases by impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha bathhouse museum, which are some rooms of old Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers from that time.
In Caesarea, it's worth visiting the exclusive private Ralli museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops there.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives ring out.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Cheers
Israel's three main tourist areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they swim even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they bathe there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that can easily hold even those who can't swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to take courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing mud and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the mysteries of ancient times
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the Citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous maritime route that linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your “same” symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, “take” the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The theater, carefully restored, is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you are traveling to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to be carried in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shequels (currently 1-3$.8 shequels).
Urban transport mainly consists of buses, but in Jerusalem there are fast trams and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City to the Upper City.
It's actually from an underground funicular.
Traveling by any type of public transport costs 6 shequels and for this price you can travel by transferring for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But on Sunday morning, a new work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, shellfish, fish without scales, and dishes that combine milk and meat.
It offers a wide selection of beef and lamb dishes, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, the falafel, which are balls of ground chickpea, fruits and vegetables.
Stray dogs are not seen on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that “walk as they please” in an imposing way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love busy places and don't turn down goodies.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
In addition to insurance, which costs $15 a day.
And renting a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to visit the country and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, an amount that is 51% higher than the same rate as in 2010, before the visa regime was canceled on February 9, 2011.
“The Great and Powerful” Will Take You to Moscow: Immigrants Save for the Language
While deputies and human rights defenders are arguing about the consequences of the law on compulsory testing, fraudsters have already appeared in the country who trade in “false” certificates
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force, according to which every working immigrant must take an exam to check their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language exam, but also the exam on Russian history and the exam on the foundations of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Citizens of countries where Russian is the official language are an exception.
Persons who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examination centers will be sponsored by the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, and right now more than 160 centers of this type are open in Russia.
The initiative on the introduction of the exam was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law took effect, managed to ask the press this question many times: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the mandatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for the immigrants themselves?
First of all, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering from “labor slavery”.
A lot of people are talking today about defending the rights of labor immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of the cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants without a profession, education, and those who do not know the language or pass medical supervision.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, take a “paid trip” to a creepy and cramped covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they promise them one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries,” confirms the Head of the Labor Immigration Directorate of the Tajikistan Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be mad, little boss!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but that they also write in their own language with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families don't even have anything to feed the children, let alone dress them, put them on shoes and buy them what they need for school.
When they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It's difficult, if you don't know the language, they recognize it.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
However, when it comes to the law on language, rights defenders make an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no exam and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers are still living in Russia illegally.
“Welcome or forbidden to strangers”
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be done quickly and for only one and a half thousand rubles.
Russian police employees know that we generally carry false documents, we are not registered, and cases of extortion appear.
“They ask us for one hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea,” the citizen of Tajikistan, Umed Hushkadamov, told reporters.
“Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting”
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several “false” certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The falsified documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought. Government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time longer to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not take drastic measures against the illegal arms trade
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is quite small
The Ministry of the Interior is proposing to apply the law more rigidly in relation to the owners of weapons for civil use.
This is the government's reaction to the recent incidents: Firing shots during wedding celebrations in which luckily there were no victims, and the massacre initiated by Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, in which seven people lost their lives.
The police want to prohibit the use and possession of traumatic weapons in public places and raise the minimum age for obtaining a license to carry weapons from 18 to 21.
This idea was supported by the head of the Duma committee on security and the fight against corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that reforms in the law on possession of arms will be brought to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy with the fact that the Russian authorities are trying to counter this problem by applying a “heavy-handed policy”.
An open letter has appeared on the internet, whose authors, representatives of various social organizations of shooters, demand that such measures of “senseless rigor” be desist.
The percentage of acts of vandalism involving the use of registered weapons is minimal, criminal lawyer Vasiliy Lesnikov told the BBC news service in Russia.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes were committed during the six months of 2012 with the use of firearms registered in interior bodies, compared to the total of 1168 crimes recorded for this same period.
The authors of the open letter are sure that stricter legislation in the field of weapons for civil use will not hinder the criminal from going to the black market.
Now, according to his words, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior states that the situation of the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The black market for arms is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are years old, says retired Colonel Victor Baranets, who for ten years worked in the Ministry of Education and in the High General Staff.
Screenshot of the website that accepts orders for weapons
The first, “vestige of the army or military”, that is, the weapons that were stolen during military actions in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by Russian officials and by Caucasians themselves,” Baranets says.
The next type of “black weapon”, those stolen by criminals and representatives of the security forces.
Baranets explains that this includes weapons stolen from police warehouses and those directly stolen by law enforcement officials.
Illegal weapons are sold from military arsenals.
In many military arsenals there were often explosions.
“There are proven versions that some fires were set deliberately to cover up the fault,” says a former military man.
According to Baranets, arms manufacturers are also doing their bit.
“Now, private arms factories that are not competitive in the international market have proliferated and distribute weapons under rope to the black market, including the one in Moscow,” says the expert.
One more source of the black market is smuggling.
A large number of guns and machine guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“They have their own production there, sometimes artisanal, and a mafia has been formed that has organized the flow of arms,” explains the former soldier.
Where do weapons come from?
Experts have calculated the approximate share of each of these sources of supplying illegal arms to the black market.
A report on this topic was prepared in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Management Planning.
The specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminological bibliography and publicly accessible data from portals whose theme revolves around weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to researchers, come from the armed forces and security forces.
Half of the weapons on the black market have arrived there “because of officials whose work is related to weapons,” the report says.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from places where there are armed conflicts, 14% of cases are stolen during weapons production and 5% correspond to “illegal archaeology”.
The shop assistant at one of the gun stores, who asked that his last name not be mentioned, says that the weapons found by illegal excavators have not been bought by anyone for a long time because they are too old.
More often, he says, suppliers head to military warehouses when they need a shipment.
Through an ensign, the supplier buys a unit, for example a TT pistol.
