“For now, fooling the brain isn't that easy”
The subject of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, has lately been perceived normally mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a model in motion and later, in November, it became known that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group in the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Izadi Sharamom, it was clarified that for the company's scientists, the glasses were already in the past.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to expand the limits of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its great mass has been stuck in the phase of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with your finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, since everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold for us?
- Although Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
The world of information technology must be freed to ours, to the physical world, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space that surrounds him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those dumb virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, it remains to be resolved the question of privacy, since we don't always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not about loose movements, but rather shorter ones.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the device's camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How is that?
- For example, how would you ask me to hand you this can of soda?
You will talk and show it at the same time.
- Usually I just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be really hard to recognize.
- In other words, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at this time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we are going to have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can precisely determine the person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, since they provide good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives algorithm designers more work.
In other words, we have to remember not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Also important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps movements are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our laboratory in Redmond, made a contact sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
An equivalent of such a device would be very useful for my work, but one that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And isn't there a need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three “cameras”, one of which is in fact the emitter of infrared rays and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible fingerboard sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analog of Kinect, play with the curvature and location of the cameras and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smartphone aloud in your hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a “transmutable” augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could go from glasses to the smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that is their strength (only you can see private things), but also their weakness: augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that manipulating virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie “Iron Man”, but also to any mere mortal.
There's a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there's no tactile response!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think that the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as an image support.
It records the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly aimed at bringing tangibility to these “images in the air”. For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what you would feel if someone were blowing on your fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think that he feels what it seems he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge that we will have to struggle with for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that they are going to an open space, almost endless. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like those in gyms), mobile platforms, as well as that of giant balloons.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, we still have to work for many years.
This is what makes working with virtual reality attractive for researchers, because many things are in a state of total conception.
