Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or colliding with a killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with humans on board set out in search of a spare planet.
To conserve humanity, the main question is asked: How to continue the species in conditions of weightlessness or on the same spare planet?
I think there is little to choose from.
In fact, only two are true planets that can be colonized, at least hypothetically.
“These are Venus and Mars,” says the chief researcher at the State Astronomical Institute, Sternberg P.K. (IAES), Vladimir Surdin.
But if the conditions on Mars are better for life, on the surface of Venus the temperature is 500 degrees.
You can only live at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
The problems of reproduction in space began to be addressed with flora.
It's been half a century since experiments with plants were carried out.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from terrestrial varieties.
Then came the breeding of insects in the orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophila.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to check how the embryo develops in conditions of weightlessness.
As a result, we get a normal chick.
But then the problems begin.
“The problem is that this chick has to find support, it must stand on its own feet and start moving,” explains Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory at the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Finding no support, the chicks would do random somersaults.
And after 10 hours the newborns had a total atrophy of instincts.
The chicks didn't react to light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they simply died.
“And twice we managed to get the chicks to be born, but then we left it because it was impossible to work there with them,” says Vladimir Sychev about the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last time a biological “miniarch” flew into orbit was 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
However, only species of the same sex will travel on the “Bion” biosatellite.
There was an experiment with rats, which were sent to space already with fetuses.
In principle, nothing supernatural was found.
“This was precisely on biosatellites, but this was a unique experiment, and studies like this must be carried out,” says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats had offspring.
However, it has not yet been possible to address the problem of reproduction directly in space.
It's a difficult challenge.
Animals, losing their usual habitat, simply cannot realize their sexual instinct.
Man, however, unlike small animals, can in principle.
Homo sapiens has abstract reasoning and is capable of creating an adequate emotional background.
Similar experiments are not conducted for ethical reasons.
But women have been traveling to space for 50 years now.
The biggest risk was passed by Tereshkova.
And the most precious thing that humanity has is the female organism.
Our seagull flying, and no one on Earth could say: if it's after a flight to space.
You may or may not have a baby after this flight.
“After all, no one has answered this question,” says aerospace veteran Vakhtang Vachnadze.
In June 1964, only a year after the flight to space, did the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, give birth to a daughter.
The girl's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut, Svetlana Savitskaya, who twice was in orbit and even worked in open space, had a son.
However, the risk persists.
There are few of us, there are few astronauts for whom everything has worked out well after long flights, and a healthy generation is growing.
“And if I can say more, it's dangerous even on orbital flights,” summarizes the cosmonaut pilot, hero of the Soviet Union, hero of Russia, Valery Polyakov.
However, humanity must seek some new ways in biotechnology, in radiological protection, in the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory of the Cosmonaut Preparation Center is a mandatory stage in preparing for the flight.
In conditions of zero buoyancy, cosmonauts practice their working skills in space.
Water simulates weightlessness.
If for an adult water is a comfortable environment, although still hostile, for a newborn child it is their native element.
Little amphibian-men seem to confirm that life on Earth emerged from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that the baby is approximately 9 months inside his mother in the amniotic fluid, since it will be easier for him to get used to the water later.
In principle, this is logical, because from the moment of birth to the time of the first bath, only 2 weeks pass.
“This is too little to forget anything,” says Marina Aksenova, a newborn swimming instructor.
In short, if weightlessness is a more natural state for a newborn, for women, gravitation, the force of gravity, is necessary.
In weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles decrease very quickly, and the ability of the fetus to expel is reduced.
Well, we omitted that, relying on the action of birth stimulants.
You can, of course, give birth in a special chamber, which will push you.
“And then what?” , Valeri Polyakov asks himself this original question.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without the sense of gravity, the body does not generate the skeleton or the muscular system.
It is impossible to dress a newborn in orbit in a special training suit, like adults.
He will simply be deprived of what is vital to him.
“And this experiment that we are going to do together, by allowing the birth of a child in a strange environment, will result in us bringing to Earth a disabled person, a totally unadapted person,” predicts the head of the bioethics committee of the Institute of Biomedical Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences, Igor Pestov.
For now, the birth of children in space is a theoretical question.
However, over time this will be a reality, when human beings in their ships head to a distant planet that will be home for their children born in space.
