What can this project actually bring? What do you think the conclusions are?
Precisely a common control of this type could help us to stop investing efforts in the implementation of laws, the reduction and improvement of limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
Savings economics means getting the right thing at a reasonable price (which doesn't always mean that the price is the lowest) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact that reducing the award limit does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much “paperwork”, that those who want to look for faults in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You talk about the problems in our country with the transfer of legislation that regulates the practice of public awards.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized differently?
As for offices, such as the NKÚ, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also to some extent similar, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of auditors are even at this level. In this respect, it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I wouldn't want to establish a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany is still a model in some ways, but it is not possible to pinpoint exactly where it is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a great number of problems.
If that weren't the case, it wouldn't benefit them to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
As for our country's legislation, what did the amendment to the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is its incidence manifested in any way?
Taking into account that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, a certain delay is necessary.
For now, we can see the process of preparing future controls: we have launched a new tool for “detecting non-economic risks”, through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and the like are rectified.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it represents an obstacle for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope that will be the case.
The problem that can arise is that the regulations “get tougher” and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programs of the regional council), and every law not respected in the area of public awards meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this journey that has begun takes us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother businessmen with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to the fact that it is autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the “švarc” system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the Office from acting, which has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, “We changed the law and allowed it,” but you can't say that we'll do as if nothing happened.
In the law on public awards, the regulations are quite strict as to how one should act formally. And that's how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded because they do not meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
Roads have ice sheets, although most of them are passable
In several parts of the Czech Republic, roads have ice and snow plaques.
Although most roads are passable, some roads must be taken with extreme caution.
Karlovy Vary Region
This morning the roads in the Karlovy Vary region were passable, but they had ice and snow sheets.
The temperature drops and will range between five and ten degrees below zero. During the day, the thermometers will rise slightly.
It has stopped snowing in the region and in the low-lying areas the snow cover is thin.
On the other hand, on the crests of the Ore Mountains, snow reaches almost 30 centimeters.
In some places, visibility was still poor because of fog, according to information from the region's highway operations control center.
The R6 highway and the first-class highway in the region are now passable without restrictions.
However, extreme caution is recommended, especially on some bridges whose surface may be icy and slippery.
In addition, all second and third category roads, including mountain roads, are also passable.
However, in some of them there are still sections with traces of ice and crushed snow.
There is a need for increased attention on the road, especially in higher areas.
Pardubice and Hradec Králové Region
On some roads in Eastern Bohemia there is a danger of frost and in higher areas and in the mountains a layer of snow may have formed on the roads, the Directorate of Roads and Highways reports on its pages.
