Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in a little less than a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It's just one of many other alarmist news that we like to hold on to.
The Tap Tap music group likes to joke about this rather, and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you are organizing a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a state charity event that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar set out for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time that the Mayan calendar ends on Kiribati Island, in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we forged the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, t-shirts, bags and original key rings against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way of supporting us.
The group The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, entitled “End of the World, Canceled”.
It's currently very popular on YouTube, can it be heard at benefit concerts?
Of course, and it will be just the last one, well, as long as everything works out and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time in all three concerts.
The hymns will be linked together simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the music video, where Xindl X also sings...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We make every effort to participate in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the money raised at the concerts against the end of the world go to?
Equipment for the Studeo barrier-free educational center, which we completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The students of the Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make this possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to create a program that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
For more detailed information, please visit www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar “spectacular action” planned in the future?
In May we will be performing for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist. Until now you have acted, for example, in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
How are the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it might seem at first glance.
There are five members in an electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to surprise me.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, where it is still uncommon for a person to move around the city center alone in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, is not there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been created that strives to discuss the problems of people with disabilities.
In what ways should we take the example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects where we are lagging behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid, it is very normal for people with serious disabilities to travel on their own in public and to be able to go to the service, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate actively in social life, in this regard, with The Tap Tap, we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, everything will begin to change for real.
Until now, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The group The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I joined Jedličkův ústav as an educator, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I am a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
However, popularity didn't come until these last few years, or am I wrong?
It's true that connecting with famous singers and also working actively to promote the group helped us a lot.
We came to the conclusion that work that cannot be seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to aid from the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that something could be done differently.
The world of show business is full of things that look like each other.
It's logical, in its own way, everything new is welcomed with caution and takes a long time to accept.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say that The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and for whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are capable of living a full life and developing themselves, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something works out for people with disabilities, then it's not just an advance for them, but for society as a whole.
Did the fact that you're a demanding boss help, as many people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many aspects and demand a certain discipline.
I think that's completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and with their heads in the clouds and when they find out that they have to attend two days to rehears, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and at concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there already at the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, it can't be helped.
Whoever has the will and desire will always find the doors open
