Poland and the Cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers from the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of ESA in the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years it participated in the agency's project committee.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already involved in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw astronomical observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study “Introduction to Cosmonautics”.
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his “Introduction to Cosmonautics”.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a dresina was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is not clear if the rocket was going to be used to start the resin or to brake it.
Information on this resin is limited to that collected in the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, Polish artillery began to focus on missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslavem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937, the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study “Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomb lotnicza”, by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all the projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemy, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
One of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future perspectives.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was finalized in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959, aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket under development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control high winds.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were differentiated from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C it was 0.62 liters.
The maximum apogee in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km above sea level.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
Suspending the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week, the constitutional court suspended the Social Work Act.
The resolution aroused a heated discussion in society.
Of course, it will be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labor costs (of salaries) causes economic tensions.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so “causes a drop” in the competitor's price with the aim of taking over most of the market and, in this way, increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most entrepreneurs, it means moving production abroad, buying there cheaper, or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the state's social spending necessarily increases.
This whole situation favors the total disinterest of businessmen in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their desire to obtain benefits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of their own population and, in this way, attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population regardless of social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes in existing laws.
The objective is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to salaries.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labor rights.
The result is growing poverty along with a widening gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid has now reached 1 million.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly common case occurs: people employed with such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind was made public related to the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
The savings measures of practically all the states in the south of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live on a terrible salary on the limits of society, in the hope that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Do we need to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media state ad nauseam that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask ourselves if private capital does not, with its selfishness, influence the political march and, therefore, on the entire state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in every state.
The result is a desperate situation that is manifested in the area of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial resources, entrust the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then approved by the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are quickly in a situation like the one described by Appiános in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic at the Time of Caesar and Pompeii: “The state had been disintegrating for some time and the administrations were occupied by force”.
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unimpeded and people went to the polls with the vote spoken beforehand”... “there were no people with character who would aspire to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state went without consuls for eight months”... “There began to be serious talk that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man”... Although Appiános was thinking of Pompeii, Caesar rose to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today's society is based on inconsiderate preferences for individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not capable, in its essence, of understanding and claiming the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as it was then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, waiting for the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the loss of hundreds of thousands in lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
Suspending the law on public awards is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue seeking other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is, therefore, systemic.
The solution involves concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in the government and that weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
