Argo Movie: If It Gets Crude, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a demonstration group of Islamist students occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive outlook: throwing the Shah overboard could not be allowed to do so, since, if it did, it jeopardized the trust of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was subsequently further intensified by the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the US, their fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran decisively contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film “Argo” by director and actor Ben Affleck focuses on an episode of this story, which achieved a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a difficult journey, they ended up at the residence of the Canadian embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran. For this purpose, a covert story helped, an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the lie seem true, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production company even had a real office.
The details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called “caper movie”, the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example could be the series Ocean's Eleven).
In the film, moods are combined. On the one hand, we found well-documented footage from Tehran. The sequence of credits shows emblematic photographs from the time of the events, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes that are somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after “Goodbye Little, Goodbye” (2007) and the thriller “The Town. City of Thieves” (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which the action doesn't take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
In addition, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates this in Argo, where Tehran is “filmed” in Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the seizure of the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity, which, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the impostor team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn't offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he copes quite well. Sometimes it adds something to reality: everything doesn't come out so elegantly here (the scene where the crisis lurks at Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its runway become crazy).
Argo's weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman play a very funny role as collaborators in Hollywood, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a little dramatic touch, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, evaluating its production and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But for it to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, that's enough.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which every year presents a survey on the most absurd bank rates, has now decided to announce the competition on “the most absurd regulations or ideas of the EU workshop”.
“It occurred to us after the last event, the EU plans to approve a 40 percent quota of women in management positions in large European companies,” explained Právo Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey.
Among the absurdities mentioned is, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance policies between men and women.
Until now, women took advantage of better prices in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk.
“Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be proposed by people until the end of this year.”
The election will take place at the end of February 2013,” Nacher reported.
Among the controversial EU regulations is, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel that, as a result, damages the environment; another prohibition is the use of lifelong mercury thermometers just because they contain a small amount of a dangerous substance or the guideline on the size of chicken cages, which has contributed to the significant increase in the price of eggs this year.
The factual prohibition of using the expression “butter spread” or the removal of the classic light bulb from shops has been criticized.
A quality banana should have a length of 14 centimeters.
The Union apparatus often takes such decisions under the pressure of one or another commercial or industrial lobby, whose requests in Brussels are normally defended by some state or group of states (the Czech Republic, even with the threat of a veto, claims the demands of its banks).
The interests of a lobby were behind the request, for example, that the highest-quality bananas in the EU should be at least 14 centimeters long and could not have “abnormal curvatures”.
The European Commission defended itself by saying that this only seeks to harmonize national standards that have not been homogenized to date, which only complicated their commercialization.
The rules referring to fruits and vegetables in the EU, despite opposition from some states, have been relaxed on the basis that the existing directive entails food waste.
The candidate to win the poll could be last year's EU prescription according to which inflatable balloons that are marketed must warn that children under 8 years of age are not allowed to inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU referred here to an American study according to which, when it comes to toys, balloons are the leading cause of infant death due to asphyxiation.
A similar restriction is also in force applicable to the use of mothers-in-law by children up to 14 years of age.
Curious occurrences are even born in our country
Equally absurd is the regulation concerning European officials: anyone who has any official function in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia. In order not to hurt Greece's sensibilities, we should talk about FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in collaboration with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated in the survey, among some absurd proposals mentioned above, the Union's prescription on the volume of food supplies in the territory of a member state.
The EU determined the maximum volumes of food supplies that can be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the same day of our entry into the EU.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volume for canned mushrooms, which posed a threat of a substantial fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the occurrence of paying those countries that do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a grant to apply for grants.
These kinds of ideas did not arise in Brussels but in Prague.
“We are at a disadvantage because we don't have a sea.
We are asking the European Union for compensation,” then agriculture minister Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) said in the fall of 2004.
He argued this with the fact that a lot of cereal was produced in our country and, as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses and had to be exported.
According to Palas, since the Czech Republic is far from seaports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
In the end, the European Commission was willing to help the Czech Republic and organized a public tender for the purchase of cereal from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The grant to receive a grant was proposed to municipalities by the Ministry for Local Development led by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU). Specifically, it is intended for drafting applications for grants from Brussels.
EU: Rare prescriptions are an exception
Member states' guidelines are often the target of criticism, and the EU's regulatory efforts and, in addition, more effective functioning and development throughout the Union deserve, according to several experts, our recognition.
According to experts, the most serious problem is, for example, the collection of EU grants for projects that have nothing to do with the deepening of European integration, but that member states have achieved in budget negotiations.
The Czechs also have a nerve, like other countries in the Union, in the fight for the right to the denomination of origin of their traditional products, even if our country has not always been victorious in these struggles.
The Czechs, after six years of disputes with Germans and Austrians, successfully defended the denomination of origin of Olomouc cottage cheese, but they had to change the name to the national rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, and was renamed “tuzemák”.
Only products made from sugar cane distillate can be called rum, but not those made from sugar beet.
In the official list of protected designations of origin in the EU, together with the feta and gorgonzola cheeses known all over the world, the marzipan from the German city Lübeck or the ham from Parma, there are, for example, cookies from Karlovy Vary, the carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň and, even, the hop variety from Žatec.
As protected gangs of the EU, they can be proud of the Pardubice gingerbread and the Hořice v Podkrkonoší wafers.
