The architectural studio MVRDV shows that real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently finished “mountain of books” - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there's finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a bystander passing by the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: “besides, the building is nice”.
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody gets into those old fashioned libraries for fun, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town on the outskirts of Rotterdam that is hardly worth a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having won a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And that's how policy makers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architectural firm MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took up the subject with her usual serenity and attended the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under her arm and a smile on her face.
And while the jury looked around in perplexity and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size in a pyramid and concluded his short speech with the following words: “Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for Spijkenisse's mountain of books, the so-called 'Boekenberg'”.
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises where it was intended.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed by an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouses.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books was awarded the second prize “Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the “Dutch National Wood Award 2012”.
In this way, the small city devoid of history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white façade one would rather guess a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese maker.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain range, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to see, the annealed brick floor and the elegant streetlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up, you can see the benches in the park, the dogs and the boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Book shelves are usually arranged along the façade and in the center there is a huge dark room that, in general, tends to be somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves, which assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a Frisian farm, we stumbled upon the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands have been using plastic fabric a few millimeters thick as a base to support the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until four centimeter thick plates were obtained.
Under heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mix of a new car and a sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us: not only do you have a fantastic view of the city from the cafeteria, but there you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it's hard to believe, given its large glass areas, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology,” Trouborst points out.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun shines inside it for only a few hours.
The huge wooden trusses located transversely to the glass façade serve to provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is up to automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Likewise, professor of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde visited the library. She describes the “Boekenberg” as Spijkenisse's “late soul”.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, for now, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has taken a deep dive.
The shelves are full.
“There's nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our initiative, all the inhabitants now have a certain connection with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved great success in that discipline that in specialized jargon is known as “creating an identity”.
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
Regardless of how young and uncultured he may be.
Finally, a starting point for shaping your identity.
