“Brand protection” in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name hides a denomination officially registered in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it is protected as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it's not clear that they will be proved right.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the law firm Taylor Wessing who specializes in violations of protective rights in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters in order to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copying themselves in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats in the Beijing brand office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities, there are multi-storey department stores dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the Pattloch cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it “Bang Ming Pai” or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term “Bang Dakuan”,
which refers to women who have “catfished” a rich man.
Chinese authorities don't feel guilty
“It's bad for business, we have to fight it,” Pattloch demands.
“The brand is running low, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the affected sectors are millions of dollars, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is, in size, the third market for luxury goods and the one that is growing at the fastest rate.
However, achieving the cancellation of dubious legal registrations in the trademark registry is difficult and also involves a lot of money.
The processes can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had passed that the name that was the subject of the lawsuit had already become a “market reality”.
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarizer because the process has damaged the plagiarizer's brand in China,” Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that was recently taken over by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities don't feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the labor emergency situation returned to normal”.
As a result, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 complaints are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is often the case in China, the numbers are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection requests, almost a third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and it means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in rights.
In other words, this means that on average each entry costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as demonstrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting a Chinese impersonator in court.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation auto parts,
the copycat has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trademark office CTMO also dismissed the Munichs' appeal.
In the next two instances, they proved Freudenberg right, but the opposing side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he will be able to resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time”.
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to one hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the opposing party a “six-figure sum in euros” with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers that lurk in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe,
specifically if imitators secure their rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register the name Freudenberg in Germany for shoes and leather products.
The group abandoned this commercial area some time ago, however it managed to prevent enrollment.
“You have to be really careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend that German companies be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international legislation on trademark rights, but what needs to be done is to “also register in China everything that may be susceptible to protection”, as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the theme can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg were to lose the last round of his private battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party licensing fees for his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would push us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: Dance, Sing, Help
In Heidelberg the Imbongi choir rehearses and in Swaziland the orphans of AIDS rejoice
The story of a bond capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers of distance.
First, it starts with dancing: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, high-heeled shoes and loafers search for the compass on the parquet floor, and they quickly find it.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the singers' voices (contralto, bass, tenor and soprano) begin to slowly rise up, getting in the way and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to almost go out of his way by trying to bring order with his energetic and gentle gestures.
It's Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg, the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song.
The fifty singers, between 23 and 69 years old, have also arrived, from the human geneticist to the housewife.
“Om'Obani” is not an easy piece, each voice in the choir has a different text and also in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations programme for the fight against AIDS, there are approximately 34 million people infected with the HIV virus worldwide.
23.5 million of them live in Southern Africa.
In Swaziland there are 245,000 AIDS orphans.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV-positive.
The association Voices for Africa has found sponsors in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans in the town of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros per month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school tuition, the uniform and will guarantee you a hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means “storyteller” or “panegyrist” in Zulu.
Nobody in this room can speak this Bantu language fluently, but they can sing.
For ten years, this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: Southern Africa.
8,733 kilometers away in a straight line from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a town called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large part of them are children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what affects Swaziland: the highest AIDS infection rate and the lowest life expectancies in the world, according to Unicef.
The population does not welcome circumcision, a practice that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of the inhabitants of Swaziland are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying at the age of just over thirty has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir discovered this remote town, but what they saw above all were many children on the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school degree, the possibilities in a poor country are more than slim.
Initially, it was only the private commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association “Voices for Africa”, which since then has been professionally caring for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts About Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Crabs and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups of people affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more often in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis registered in Germany are caused by sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonads, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively rare; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between 15 and 25 years old.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were recorded.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that this is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often don't cause pain or cause other symptoms and are therefore not detected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they don't offer 100% protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through dirt infections and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change your sexual partner.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any delayed consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, the fees charged by the choir for its performances throughout Germany, they raise quite a lot of money.
“In total, we have already sent some 200,000 euros to Esitjeni,” says Annette Lennartz, president of the association, proudly.
In the village itself, Zodwa Dlamini, a confident woman with leadership skills manages the money sent from Germany.
It ensures that orphans find good housing, for example with one of their grandmothers.
