According to Annette Lennartz, “On any corner you can get free condoms, but they are hardly used.
It's another culture, here they only accept skin-to-skin contact.”
To promote cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two or three years to Southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, fighting spirit, hope and trust in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost tip of the African continent still remember from the apartheid era.
A bus full of white people singing songs in a black language; so much recognition not only brings an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but it has also managed to tear a couple of tears out of the odd angry border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Esitjeni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Although this small town barely appears on maps, it is well known in the valley of the Ezulweni River.
“Come closer to Esitjeni, the light shines there,” say the locals.
And after traveling the 8,733 kilometers in a straight line back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms on Bergheimer Street full of singers marking the way, one realizes that it is also possible to see their light shining from there.
