The journey through the mountainous region of Talysh could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus travels with a loud clap along the winding road that passes next to forested hills, high-flowing rivers and the simple homes of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, one might even think that you are in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost area of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
The “Talyshi” live here, a town about which not much is known, apart from the fact that they are perfectly fluent in Persian and Azerbaijani and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts an architecture that may be too massive, designed in the Soviet era and that doesn't seem to fit quite into such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists barely reach this place, as the road from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate the two urban centers, eight hours are needed because the road is one-way.
The astonishing wealth that the country enjoys thanks to oil from the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
“Baku became famous in May on the occasion of the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will celebrate the Festival of the Oldest People in the World,” says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Longevity Museum, perhaps the only one that exists in the world.
The lives of eight dozen local talyshis who are over 100 years old are documented here. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
One of his children died at the age of 136.
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the shepherd Şirali Müslümov, who seems to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate that certifies it.
And if we consider that the oldest documented man lived 122 years, it seems that Müslümov's age is quite suspicious.
“He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973,” Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children. Apparently she still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
So has Şirali Müslümov been wrong about his age in a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
“In some regions of China, Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan, very old people also live,” says Scholz, “even in Sardinia there are many older men.”
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific evidence about age; especially when there is no civil registry either.
Every day glasses full of melted butter
It is a fact that, surprisingly often, the inhabitants of the region around Lerik tend to reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people over 100 years of age.
Why do so many elderly people live here in the south?
Azerbaijani tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains that these are the special genes of Talyshis.
Instead, the director of the museum, Mrs. Fatulayeva, believes that nutrition is the cause.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it doesn't seem logical that precisely the high-calorie diet of the Talyshi, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of whom, in addition, drink a glass of melted butter every day, is so healthy.
Or maybe it's the natural way of life that keeps people young? Rubaba Mirzayeva lives in Cengemiran, a small settlement not far from the city of Lerik.
At 97 years old, he is relatively young for what he is in style in these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
Sitting on the floor, she relentlessly moves a huge tub of butter.
Eight people live under a roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, both of whom became grandparents a long time ago.
Two small children are also jumping from one side to the other.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea that is served in typical domed glasses.
Mirzayeva's teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under her handkerchief she hides two long braids of dark blonde hair that her son proudly reveals to us.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen out and has maintained its color.
“I've never used a shampoo either,” Mirzayeva says.
The pension is enough to live on
He has always eaten only what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
In all my life I have never been shopping in a supermarket.
Then she tells us about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst was the era after World War II.
However, everything returned to its course when the “dear father”, Heydar Aliyew, took control of the situation.
This kind of propaganda sounds weird on the lips of an older woman.
However, in Azerbaijan, the cult of the nation's father figure, who runs his country like a dictator, knows no bounds.
He remained in power until 2003, when he handed over the baton to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly in Azerbaijan don't know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva earns 230 manat (approximately the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount that can be lived well considering the situation here.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's gray-haired son is right: “in our culture the elderly are highly respected.”
They live in a big family, are loved, receive all the necessary care and are happy.
As if that wasn't enough reason to stay alive for many years...
The Constitution lacks the expression “Human Rights”
The revolution has returned to Cairo.
Rivalling demonstrations in Cairo highlight the tremendous division in which the country is mired.
The future constitution, with sharia as its basis, is highly controversial.
The Egyptian president did not skimp on pathos.
“We must overcome the transition.
And for that to happen is my responsibility, before the people and before God,” he said on public television.
His speech was addressed to all the people, especially Coptic Christians, liberals, enlightened Muslims and the secular.
All of them, hopelessly mired so far in confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a theocracy on the banks of the Nile by the grace of the powerful Muslim community.
As Mohammed Mursi explains, almost asking for forgiveness, he has had to temporarily annul the powers of the Constitutional Court and expand his “in order to save the revolution”.
However, neither the Egyptians nor the whole world know very well what this 61-year-old engineer with a doctorate degree from the University of Southern California really wants to save.
Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
In fact, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members in a 15-hour evening meeting, are truly worrying.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on “principles of Islamic law”.
However, what does “principles” mean?
This was and continues to be open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal room for maneuver that comes with it, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what a new added article suggests: on all issues related to sharia, it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power in all of Sunni Islam.
This need not be the case, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that would - in fact - result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation.
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During the Mubarak dictatorship, these courts served to exert harsh repression on the opposition.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were being held in military prisons.
As stated in the draft, the State must protect “the true essence of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values”.
This formulation is so vague in legal terms that, with the help of this article, state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
Clearly speaking, this is nothing more than censorship.
Of course, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
On the other hand, another prohibits offending or slandering Prophet Mohammed and his legates.
However, it is not clear what an offence is and how it should be sanctioned.
Equally dubious is the formulation that prohibits “offending people”
Is a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
A matter of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for signature and which, according to his words, “very soon” will be presented to the Egyptians to be submitted to a referendum.
“The revolution is back”
For weeks, the opposition has been closing ranks in the face of the superiority of the Islamists.
Ten thousand people gathered in unusual harmony on Friday afternoon in Tahrir Square in Cairo on Friday afternoon and vowed to overturn the Act before it could enter into force.
“The revolution has returned and we will end up winning,” says Hamdin Sabbahi, who is third on the lists for the presidential elections.
The Nobel Peace Prize winner and former director of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, stated that the draft constitution should be “in the dustbin of history”.
Through Twitter, he accused Mursi's followers of wanting to lead a “coup against democracy”.
“When he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him,” says opponent Jasser Said.
“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned for,” opposition politician Chaled Ali was quoted in the Egyptian media.
And several judges announced that they did not want to oversee the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
“The Quran is our constitution”
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-demonstration; just in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, in front of the University of Cairo.
Many women covered with veils and supporters of the Salafists took part in it, shouting: “the people demand the application of the divine law”.
They demanded that Morsi “clean up the country”, at the same time they proclaimed: “the Quran is our constitution”.
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where it all began, would have caused a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It's obvious that Morsi's supporters didn't want to risk something like that happening.
The Muslim Brotherhood said that both those who oppose the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their opinions loud and clear.
Now would have come the time to let the people decide at the polls what direction the country should follow.
In this sense, it seems that the Islamists' draft has the majority guaranteed.
“The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear”
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious at this forced constitutional process, which in reality should have lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old lawyer specializing in human rights and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended the Muslim brothers when they were being held in prison or had to face trial during the Mubarak dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason, he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
“And now the expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear in the new constitution,” she laments in a conversation with the newspaper “Welt am Sonntag”.
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three branches of government led this lawyer to resign himself.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it,” Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot work without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could backfire on you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: “you are conceiving a monster that you cannot control.”
Norwegian Rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway's five million people enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has anything to do with its hunger for an extremely smelly fish?
Eat a series of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, damp soccer clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing scent of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowy. The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that can be fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how smelly you prefer it.
As it gets dark and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat it raw and then drink a glass of Aquavit in one gulp,” says Havard Halvarsen, a firefighter from the city who is also known as the “General of Rakfisk”, who is responsible for organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking significant quantities of the drink in one gulp.
“Some people like aquavit better than rakfisk,” Havard says.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'm trying some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, that's not bad; it's not much different from a piece of sushi that has been traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty hit Norway and when, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, obviously with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and mainly migrated to the United States.
Currently, the population is increasing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high salaries and a complete system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants from Sweden, the old rival and until not too much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered something important, an essential, if quite smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But in fact, everything is expensive. A pint of beer or a sandwich costs a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway is not usually on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it that way.
People here are still unwilling to say the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who gunned down and murdered 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22nd event.”
Norwegians have a hard time believing that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth is the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil isn't the only reason why we're doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she passes Rakfisk trays and who, with her long blonde hair and surprising blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, prudent people.”
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
“We don't like to brag, we don't like to show off.”
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything, except for a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money that they didn't have during the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we're happy,” Anna says.
“And eat rakfisk,” he adds with an unwrapped laugh.
I'm in the snow waiting in line for something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now an elk burger is undoubtedly something different and quite succulent to savor.
But at night, that stinky fish returns.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a Rakfisk dinner is held in which diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a presenter who wears a bow tie and who is surrounded by Rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision contest.
“What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?”
“Here's our score, Havard.”
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls out of his chair, perhaps beaten by the Aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
While the incoming President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, is preparing to take office, the BBC correspondent, Will Grant, analyzes the challenges that the new president will face and the different expectations of his population.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad today.
In a city that, under the best circumstances, is already already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads that lead to the city and that is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The objective, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their place of work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
It is faced with a complicated task.
Mexico has been achieving good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is submerged in a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government is deeply committed to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Mr. Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to the President of the United States, Barack Obama, in the Oval Office.
“I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal.”
Before rubbing shoulders with the President of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state, that of Mexico.
A highly populated and rapidly growing state that surrounds the capital; opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it for the growth of local tourism and for the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city, you can drive along one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new highways, which represents an enormous improvement compared to the cracked and bumpy roads that were renovated.
You can also see plaques with his name at the entrance of a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
“We trust that he will be able to achieve real and lasting change,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a member of Mr. Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
“In particular, when it comes to security and economy, we look forward to the interesting and real change that our country so badly needs.”
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was overthrown by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Deputy Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, within the party there are many expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opposition's qualification of the lack of essence of the new president.
“He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He's a fantastic statesman and, above all, he's a person who knows how to listen.”
However, on the other side of the state, that is not the impression that many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobblestone streets of Valle del Bravo couldn't be greater.
Tucked away under elevated stretches of highway, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also tough and urban.
Earlier this year, the intervention of the military was called for to help in the fight against drug gangs operating in neighborhoods, and violence against women is especially serious.
In a desert plot, located next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, that he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
The most critical accuses their administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make an effort to hold back her tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
“When I arrived at her house, it looked as if her body had been cleaned,” Mrs. Buendía recalls.
“There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared.”
While her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana observes from the walls, next to a cross that reads a single word: Justice.
However, that is exactly what the family says he has been denied.
“The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
What they want is for you to simply accept what they say and to shut up.”
“But that can't be the case when there have been so many wrongdoing and so much negligence,” he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by enormous responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years, and the new president has promised to give them priority during his term in office.
“I hope he's the same type of president he was when he was governor,” says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning didn't report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's time at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the biggest leak of confidential information in United States history, lost multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while under military detention.
During the prosecution's interrogation of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of weekly visits from officers of the unit that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing held following the defense's request that the case be dismissed because his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was incarcerated under maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers allegedly asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the warders as “excellent” and the treatment received at the facility in general as “very professional.”
The forms don't show any allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had talked about those problems and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the registry.
“They would write 'no incident' (after talking about the problems) but that doesn't necessarily mean that I wouldn't have mentioned any problems,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he hadn't reported the treatment he was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a council charged with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the “injury prevention” regime under which he was.
The military said they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the general staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so that I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had considered committing suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning explained Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in that cage.”
Manning said that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of his days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said that he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said that he always had light from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said that if the guards couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that he would turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's statement, according to which, after being forced to sleep naked one night in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning recount to stand naked in front of warders and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the recount.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said that she deduced from the order given to her by the warden that she should drop the blanket with which she could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered her to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic in his underwear or his flip flops to harm himself but that he hadn't.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he were convicted in the court-martial, which is due to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to make Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is due to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules applicable to any detainee in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperating with the enemy, unlawfully causing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If found guilty on all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He states that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette says that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had barely walked down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and I was already totally confused.
Some signs indicated the way to two queues: one for “Mexicans” and the other for “Foreigners”.
I stayed there for a few seconds not sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I have been called “Mexican” throughout my life.
This is ethnic shorthand, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as “Irish” or my friends in New York describe themselves as “Italian”.
Later I decided on “Mexican-American”.
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts weren't necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native speaker and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the queue of foreigners.
I thought of that time this week when the elected president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda for the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, included: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also keen to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why a Mexican is currently as likely to stay in Mexico as to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trading bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a United States official says anything that involves the slightest criticism of Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And Moctezuma's children stand up in arms.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really represents quite a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Are we talking about bitterness?
There's a lot.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom this is not the case.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities such as Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere in our family tree, there was a person, perhaps the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who had to leave the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor town, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican dream.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans who belong to the elite of the ruling class don't like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulders as if we were from a lower category that isn't Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either of them.
We love listening to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best from each country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things even more, from what I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as impromptu “ambassadors” for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American colleagues how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would pressure political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
That's not going to happen.
There's too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us aren't so sure that it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, friends.
It's fair.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful about how their families were treated much, much less time ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more “Mexican” than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the futile and usual discussions about who started first, lots of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, even though the Israelis and the Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in pieces whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional uproar.
Perhaps this will make their fight even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their deadly deadlock situation could be unraveled.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism currently seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is maintained, this week's clashes have reinforced falcons on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has governed Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has taken a good beating.
And despite having killed some of its leaders and putting pressure on the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to put an end to Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently governed by its relentless rivals from Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that time is in their favor.
As Islamists have been gaining influence across the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas. So has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
The exultant members of Hamas say that the Islamist half moon is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the militia-party Hezbollah dominates, through Syria, where rebels with an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populated and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, didn't have much time for Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood are first cousins of Hamas and their leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hardliners will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military question is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven effective and many of Hamas's missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis will sleep more peacefully... for some time.
As for diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for starting the latest wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered. Especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
