The generic tobacco packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases appear on dull green packs, which are the same for all brands of tobacco
The Australian law on tobacco and generic packaging, a pioneer in the world, comes into force and replaces the logos and colors of the brands with a dull olive green wrapper, appalling images of parts of the body with diseases and depictions of children and babies sick because they are the children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the packs, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a small type of font.
This is the strictest regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
Australia's federal government says the goal is to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
Trust studies that show that if a person hasn't started smoking before the age of 26, there's a 99% chance that they never will.
“You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and that these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals much, other countries are considering taking similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black market for tobacco, in which cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
“The legislation will have serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre, of British American Tobacco, in Australia.
The amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia will increase.
Other people say that their business has benefited after the law was passed.
Sandra Ha, from Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said that demand for silicone cigarette cases and covers to cover up the unpleasant images on the packs had skyrocketed almost from zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in the Supreme Court of Australia.
Ms. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and that she was waiting for more stocks.
“For us it's good business.”
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector targeted by the plan.
Following a series of Australian laws that prohibit television advertising and sports sponsorship and requiring most retailers not to put cigarettes in plain sight, tobacco marketing has now taken place online.
Australia has banned Internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but it cannot restrict it on foreign pages.
“If you sell tobacco and you only have this small window left to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman saw an increase in brand reviews from “ordinary citizens” published on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if he is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
Australia's British American Tobacco indicated that the industry focuses more on what the new regulations entail than on marketing.
The industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules; these countries are stating before the World Trade Organization that trade is being unjustly restricted, despite the fact that none of these countries have a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said that the government had held talks with other countries that are considering applying similar laws on tobacco packaging.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the requirement to include images in packs.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia, many smokers are challenging.
“The photographs don't affect me.
I just don't listen to them.”
“You pick up the cigarette and keep the package,” says Victor El Hage as he buys a package with an image of a tumor in his mouth.
“Honestly, there's only one reason I would quit smoking: for my daughter.”
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack tobacco shop in downtown Sydney, says that the uniform packs make it more difficult for him to place them on the shelves.
“It normally took an hour to unpack a delivery; now it takes four hours,” says Yu.
“The government should have completely banned tobacco and then, that's it, okay, it's over and we closed the store,” he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to get a little bored
During the Thanksgiving holiday this year, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours in an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not going to lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have ways to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention duty-free stores.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it's okay for both us and our children to get bored from time to time.
Being bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don't experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Yes.
And no.
But, we'll talk about that later.
First of all, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as stated by Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, in Canada, and author of the book “Boredom: A Lively History” (“Boredom, a Lively History”) published in 2011 by Yale University Press, this is not the case.
“In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom that date back to the first century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways,” says John D. Eastwood, professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining published research and presenting the idea to a discussion group made up of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “wanting, but not being able to, participate in an activity that fills you up”.
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn't do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly”.
Boredom can sound awfully similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider that they have the problem.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what's really happening to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In their study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention”, published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a television program at full volume in the next room that was not related, others listened to it at a low volume, so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group never heard the audio.
The group that listened to the program at low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it was difficult for them to concentrate, but they weren't sure why and they attributed it to boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of attention can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph, in Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
“On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, such as detecting faulty parts on a manufacturing line, distracting music can help you not get bored.”
“In fact, we now know that moving or doodling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, since they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to be bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to be bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a “boredom tendency scale” in the 80s.
The scale includes questions such as “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do everything”.
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of Psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys are more likely to be bored more often than girls, and specifically they need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren't in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he didn't know if today's boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said that what he did know was that “adolescence is a period in which boredom reaches its highest levels”, largely because both children and adolescents are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it isn't, since, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to be exposed to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into substance use as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this question for more than two decades.
“Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, you might be satisfied in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he won't have learned to entertain himself or to dose himself,” says Professor Fenske.
And “that ability to be dosed applies to other situations,” he says.
Not only does your child learn to be entertained on their own, but they learn to control themselves better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant noise of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to be more bored, but boredom is a desire that is too distressing and disturbing to be related to anything worthwhile,” he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy some downtime.
“In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it's difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise ceases.”
Colorado: No instruction book for the new law on marijuana use
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old student at a community institute and soccer player in southeastern Colorado, is facing criminal prosecution for something that will soon be legal throughout the state: the possession of marijuana stones and a pipe that he used to smoke it.
Orozco says that one day in September, he and some friends were driving through Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, when police stopped them.
The police found marijuana in the car and some time later Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and related items (misdemeanors that each carry a fine of 100 US dollars) informing him of the date of the trial.
“They treat us like criminals,” Orozco says.
And are they?
In the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado's vote to legalize possession of small quantities of marijuana for recreational use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of misdemeanor crimes for possession of marijuana are being overturned both here and in the state of Washington, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped bringing charges against those over 21 years old for small-scale possession, which will be legally passed once the law takes effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors from more conservative districts in Colorado have pledged to move forward with open cases for possession of marijuana and are still subpoena people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent newly licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“All of this is changing so quickly that I don't know what's next,” said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those in charge of regulations in the state of Washington are also thinking about the matter.
And they are still seeking advice to establish a licensing system for production, manufacturing, distribution and sales, all before the deadline of December 1, 2013.
They say that, for better or worse, Colorado is ahead of most states when it comes to regulating the use of marijuana, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide,” says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Control Commission.
But Mr. Smith admits that any place or system can only make suggestions about what might work.
“There is no real precedent to serve as a model for us,” he says.
Washington's law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6, which also leaves a year during which we will swim between two waters, since the licensing system in that state will not yet exist, but possession will be legal.
In addition, there are some sensitive mechanical issues that must be resolved during this period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state's requirement to provide “adequate access” to authorized marijuana and its prohibition of conducting cannabis businesses within a radius of less than 300 meters from schools, parks, children's play areas or children's centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” says Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently created research group.
On November 21, Oates, the Aurora police chief, sent an email to his police officers informing them that the city prosecutor would stop bringing lawsuits for minor misdemeanors for possession of marijuana against people over 21 years of age and that the police would stop bringing charges against those crimes “with immediate effect.”
Police Chief Oates said that they would be responsible for enforcing the city's regulations that regulate the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and that they would continue to pursue drug traffickers and sellers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, district attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he assured that his office would continue to pursue cases of possession of marijuana, mainly to pressure consumers into deciding to receive treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
“Our office has an obligation to bring legal action against misdemeanors that were criminal offences at the time they occurred,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The answer has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the initiative to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer cites adults for possession of small quantities.
Pete Hautzinger, county district attorney, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
“I don't think I'm wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes,” he said.
Although 55 percent of voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana use into the government and the judicial system was never considered to be easy.
The contradictory reactions that arise across the state reveal a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the great environmental experiment in this state.
“This is a cultural barrier with district attorneys,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents those accused of possession of marijuana and who is a local spokesperson for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Law.
“They've spent so much time taking people to court that, in reality, they still can't accept that it's legal,” he said.
As the first states to consider small quantities of marijuana in the same way as if it were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become the national test cases in terms of drug legalization.
While lawyers and state officials have a new frontier of legal sales, they are also looking forward to receiving guidance from the federal government, which still expects the sale and cultivation of marijuana to be considered as federal crimes.
Advocates of the legalization of marijuana are hoping that the Department of Justice will give in.
Although there have been some notable arrests of patients and sellers of marijuana for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has mostly allowed businesses selling marijuana for these purposes to exist in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
“Although drug agents probably won't break down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they will probably be reluctant to allow state-regulated stores to operate for the sale of marijuana for recreational use, allowed under the new law,” said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy advisor to the Obama administration.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local governments passed moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, even though it will be about a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to approve it next week.
“We don't want to put ourselves in a situation where we authorize someone and then have a serious problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
“Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying for what the community voted for versus voting for what the state voted for.”
A lot of questions arise in this regard.
Petronella Wyatt: “I was harassed until I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory”
University students aren't attacked for their views just now
I can't remember a time in my life when I haven't been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been to what I supposed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary Greek symposium that promoted the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, two weeks after taking my place at Worcester College in the late 80s to study History, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down and burst into tears.
My friends were baffled.
The Evening Standard newspaper stated that I had dropped out because I didn't tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I had left because they forced me to drink from broken cups.
The truth was less fun.
I fled from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subject to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my quirky name, not because of the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, which in the cradle of the supposed Enlightenment was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a leading advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the conservative party.
You may be wondering what that's coming up for now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of students from the Conservative Party is such that, last week, a group of them called for the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the JCR (undergraduate student group) of Corpus Christi College say that they are “often seriously separated, personally attacked and treated as unwelcome people” because of their political ideas.
They want to create a seat on the equal opportunities committee of their university college to ensure that they can express their opinions freely.
Their situation was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called “Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right” (Paradise: Young, Bright and on the Right) about student politics, which presented the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazis.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a walking stick with a silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say that they are treated like “scapegoats” because of the introduction of higher tuition rates.
Luke Black, 20 years old and vice-president of the Conservative Party Association of the University of Nottingham, stated in a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing left-wing tendency in universities.
People assume we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student in Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says that this environment is “uncomfortable”, while Stephanie Cherill, 19, and elected president of the OUCA, says that the attitude of the members of the JCR towards people who are from the center right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered the university in September 1986. I was a terribly shy 18-year-old girl.
Hate for the Conservative Party was at an all-time high.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an “honorary degree” after cuts in funding for higher education.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with horror.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming the new university students, when the new students met and the professors, I received a taste of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery that was made of conservative university students, but that they were willing to participate in it.
The politics of the miners' strike, privatization and the government's opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the wooden rooms of the seminary.
The first one I attended had to be translated into English French texts from the 18th century and I wasn't prepared for what came next.
“Miss Wyatt,” said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), “please translate the first paragraph.”
Don't say a single one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew very well how to expel bad bile.
“Are Thatcherists refusing to learn French, or are they simply dumb?” , he asked.
The other university students laughed.
My eyes burned from the tears I was trying to hold back.
“I suggest that you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you're not too busy meeting people,” Pitt growled.
I returned to my room like a grieving soul.
That night I sat alone at dinnertime at the university; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he told me kindly.
“I'm afraid that's how it's going.
They mess with anyone suspected of being Tory.
It's very difficult for me, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be even worse for you.
A lot of newly arrived Tories appear to be Labour.”
Later on, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to disguise.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved futile.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated.”
Other students adopted that little tune.
I became the dirty pervert.
“How do the Tories have sex?” , one asked.
“They beat each other up, don't they?”
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 60s.
Could I one day lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet people who thought like me only after nightfall?
Would I have to become a Labour Party and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my university college.
They hated him because he was not only a member of the Conservative party, but also an advisor to Thatcher on foreign policy and one of the people who wrote his speeches for him.
It was barely around there.
He hated the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist vision of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You're not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I began to commute daily from Oxford to my parents' house in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded, metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he was studying there in the 1940s, all political points of view were accepted.
“But if it's the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
“They would never do that, not there among my dear dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude.”
His sore eyes started to blur.
“Give it another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you left him.”
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of History had insinuated, speaking totally seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people”, I decided to do the same.
Red with embarrassment inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “stupid old men”.
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
Back then, my father was writing two weekly columns in Murdoch's press.
My door was locked with a key.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
Maybe you'll call me a weeping weakling.
But no 18-year-old should be subject to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 prime ministers of the Conservative party but, to this day, is hiding behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
“Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety”
On the occasion of the exhibition “Valentino: Master of Sewing”, which opened this week in London, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer recognized him during the inauguration of “Valentino: Master of Sewing”, a tremendous retrospective that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his “maison” over the past 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says in his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose only protagonist is “Il Signore” Garavani, but which could not have been written without its distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rarefied and distant world of nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, private letters and photos abound with the signature of the most granary of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, through Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a humble couturier from the city of Voghera, in northern Italy, to an idol of the international “jet set”.
There's nothing wrong with being in love with royalty.
“At least they don't put out the cigarette butts on your gorgeous rug like some beautiful pop music celebrities do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we were both living in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains generously and elegantly.
“We all loved being invited to her chalet in Gstaad,” explains the ex-wife of “Heini” Thyssen, intimate with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to notoriety.
And yet, it's a star.
Valeria Mazza, wearing a Valentino
The Argentinian model Valeria Mazza doesn't forget the couturier's charisma either.
Many years ago, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna, in Rome, we went to his apartment for dinner.
We were twenty people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of the apartment, the decor, the food, the music, in everything you could see and feel his spirit.
“He made each of the guests feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model”, who began working with him during the Paris Haute Couture Week in 1995.
“It never goes out of style because its designs are works of art,” he concludes.
Alcurnia fashion show
Garavani's life is not a story of obsessions, but of well-requited loves.
He loves people with good education and better degrees, and they love him.
One of the Somerset House galleries has been transformed into a glamorous sixty meter-long runway that proposes a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of the models and must walk down the runway to contemplate a dreamy “audience” that wears masterpieces by Valentino, such as the dress that Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding with Aristotle Onassis, the wardrobe that Monica Vitti used in “La Notte”, or a wool and leather coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience of mannequins, names such as Sibylla from Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia from Habsburg shine.
Naty Abascal and the couturier, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino is like their first love, “impossible to forget”.
I remember it perfectly.
It was pants, a shirt, a “Gillette” vest and a jacket from the 1971-1972 autumn-winter collection.
