The toughest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone trails
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphurous gas that emanates from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with air.
After tearing up large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb at a snail's pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall off the cliff.
They know that any setback could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell down the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, painstakingly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) for every kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
“Since it's normal to carry 70 kilos, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three daily transfers.
It takes three hours each and it ends up ground, but they allow you to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a misery for such an inhumane effort, it is triple what I would earn on the field.
“The miners' wage is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the porter, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the slash wasn't as hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a weighty reason that, in Indonesia, is as overwhelming as sulfur: “I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam.”
Anto has asthma, breathes hard, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At 27 years old, Anto has been playing his ass at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes hard, he coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
It's the price you must pay to achieve your dream.
“I will work for two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because sulfur doesn't stop flowing at night, when his characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the dark.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater with light from a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself bought with his money.
Some 400 porters carry the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its enormous benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs, nor does it supply any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and at so much weight.
In fact, they don't even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, together with the entry of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the rangers of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for beasts and not for people,” protests Madrusin, a stocky 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, she says she will endure working “as long as she can” because she needs the money to educate her three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps miners in the thick columns that emerge from the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious illnesses... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder sores, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his colleagues remove 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a goat path through the weeds.
“I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30 years old, also works carrying sulfur.
Time goes by, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest jobs in the world: the one done by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
“Singapore's population needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let's do our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unlikely that these verses are part of an advertisement for peppermint pills, but despite that - or perhaps because of that - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references such as “Let's put a bath (bun) in the oven” to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that with the announcement they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to make people do “their national duty”.
This is purely an internet thing, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt that this was a topic we needed to address.
We knew that the government had tried a lot of things, such as launching pheromone perfumes or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do as creative as possible to solve this problem, which is to write a rap?
1.2 children
The one that doesn't take it so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it's due to “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and starting a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in singleness, and to delaying marriage and births, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy that aims to dramatically increase immigration to address the decline in the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where xenophobia in disguise abounds against many new immigrants, in particular Chinese immigrants, who are criticized for keeping salaries low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore's governing party experienced its worst electoral result since independence.
Since the elections, there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the drop in the birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has come to control the number of small apartments, known as “shoe boxes”, that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the real estate company EL Developers, says that their “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hindered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district doesn't seem like they're going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so is education, so a lot of people are putting it off,” says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
“But it's important for me to have my own money and time,” says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is about the quality of private or “the area of private life that one has the right to protect from any interference”.
What is private for a child under 16?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and on social media?
Do you understand the dangers you're exposed to by airing situations on the Internet that you probably wouldn't share offline?
El Periódico interviewed five boys between the ages of ten and 15, who are frequent users of the network.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with “something very mine”, on a personal level, and “in the username and password”, when they applied it to social networks.
“I wouldn't post my deepest secrets,” says Jorge, 10, when he tries to explain the meaning of private on sites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
“These are very secret secrets, my mom can know them, but not everyone,” she says.
On FB I upload beautiful images or images of games.
I also have fun with my acquaintances.
“I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or of someone who's making a fool of themselves,” he says.
The child recognizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, of naked people, of crimes, or to write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother is included, she has the password to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends quickly,” he says.
He doesn't hesitate to answer that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
Nor would I listen to someone who recommended him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The adolescent has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, in the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his list of friends.
“It doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, music for example,” he says.
According to the boy, none of them have been insinuated or asked for his home address or telephone number.
“If they pressured me or demanded it from me, I just took them out of my account,” he admits.
José became a follower of Ask, after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
An acquaintance of a friend of mine was being extorted on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money from him.
“He never knew who he was,” he says.
The victim, according to José, did not close the account.
“He just gave it privacy.”
It then explains a series of steps to set up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yes, he would, if I don't like him or feel like it.
“Although I know that's cyberbullying,” he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet emerged as a means of searching for information, but with the appearance of these sites, the rules of the game changed,” he says.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, a master's degree in Pedagogy from Yale University and author of the work Digital Natives and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who were born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, when we are still learning,” he says.
He comments that the topic is complex, “because we are asking them to have a definite criterion on what should or should not be disseminated, published or said at an age when maturity is not enough for that.”
“They should also be selective when what matters most to them is being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” he adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach what privacy is to children and adolescents is through questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it doesn't work,” he adds.
Next, Porras lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a photo of you like the one you posted of a friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask other people for permission to tag them?
And one more, does everyone need to know what you're doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they should act online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
“Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, just as it should be on social networks,” he says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, elementary school teacher and educational consultant, comments that it is essential for parents to read social media policies conscientiously.
By understanding each of the paragraphs, they have a solid foundation for talking with their children about the implications of opening an online account.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
According to Guardia, reminding children of the lesson of “don't talk to strangers” is key.
UNASUR Summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders, being made public.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Regular Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially indicated that they would deliver it after the closing, but later stated that at some point it will be published on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the content had been presented by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information from the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message “private session, restricted audio” was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was provided by the press spokesmen of some of the UNASUR governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but this is Humala's statement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated either.
On the official ASPA website, it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made every effort to ensure that there were secure transmission systems for all journalists, but limited the collection of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a decision of the Court of The Hague that would settle a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
“We will abide by and execute the judgment that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today,” said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts,” Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake, along with the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia this week denounced the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held with the absences of the Brazilian presidents, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the event.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were established for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the agreements on residence.”
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to the internet at low prices in all corners of South America, and to address the risks of natural disasters together and efficiently.”
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of spaces in South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” said the Peruvian president in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace, and of good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this regard, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he expected to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to deal respectfully with the maritime dispute after a decision of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
“Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua,” he stressed.
“With President Ortega, I hope to be able to tell him that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of that country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, as part of the summit, the bloc's defense ministers met beforehand to approve the Action Plan for the year 2013, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense issues in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although the last country has been suspended.
Peru has the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
“South America must learn from Europe to integrate a citizenry”: Rafael Correa
The president of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, said today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which “South America, in this case yes, must learn from Europe.”
