The Ecuadorian president also considered “perfectly pertinent” the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate the maritime boundaries between the two countries with Nicaragua after the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which benefited Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty.
For the time being, that ruling is not being complied with.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They need to be processed comprehensively in order to overcome them and move forward.
He also hoped for a successful conclusion of the maritime boundary litigation that Peru and Chile maintain in the same court and opined that “it is right for Latin America to seek international instances if the two countries are committed to accepting a judgment no matter how tough it may be.”
In reference to the possibility that he will run as a candidate in the next presidential elections in Ecuador to seek a third consecutive term, he said that he sees that possibility “with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite hard.”
Correa said that if he loses the February 2013 elections, he will retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as Ecuador, that socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
“My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed that probable victory, because we have to accept that responsibility,” he said.
If I win it would be my last term in office and from there we left public life.
If we lose anyway.
“It's a decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez's new health treatment in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he tells me that he traveled to a treatment that was already planned, routine, that the campaign to return to Cuba was expected to pass.
“It doesn't mean a relapse in President Chávez's state of health,” he said.
