Deaths due to AIDS today are a cause of late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: positive for AIDS.
“It was as if a bomb fell on me,” he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor was trying to make “softer”, with no obvious success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; with such commitment that he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 90s, when there were a lot of doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him “because he had a cut”.
So, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
However, ignorant of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked haVOC, “exhausted” their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, at least among the first reported cases, “the great achievement means right now that the survival of a patient who begins treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same,” said the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after stating that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS expert, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectations for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years, when they report 500 CD4.
