Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth (Texas), became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as “J.R.”, in the television series “Dallas”, in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series “Dallas” became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of “Dallas,” died Friday afternoon due to complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the producer of “Dallas.”
“Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he liked the most,” the family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of her wife in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when she died in a Dallas hospital, said her publicist, Jeffrey Lane.
It brought joy to everyone I met.
He was creative, generous, fun, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him dearly.
“He was an original person and lived life to the fullest,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and acknowledged that he had been drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and he underwent a transplant.
Years before “Dallas”, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy “I Dream of Jeannie”, broadcast on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he finds an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his house.
He also starred in two comedies that were on the air for a short time, “The Good Life” (NBC, 1971-72) and “Here We Go Again” (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically-acclaimed roles in “The Group”, “Harry and Tonto” and “Primary Colors”.
But it was his masterful portrayal of the enchantingly detestable J.R. that brought Hagman to his greatest stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its orbit aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase “Who shot J.R.?” , designed to generate expectation around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman was almost murdered, generated international speculation and millions of risky dollars in bookmakers.
It also helped give the series a record viewership at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in and made “Dallas” the second most watched entertainment program in history, behind the end of “MASH” in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to call her a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be institutionalized.
“I know what I want on J.R.'s headstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, “Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing.”
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone “huge, on and off screen”.
It's unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each one of us, who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of “Dallas” were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five of the episodes for the second season had already finished and a sixth was in progress, the network reported.
There was no immediate statement from Warner or TNT about how the series will handle the loss of Hagman.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classic works such as “South Pacific” and “Peter Pan”.
Martin was still a teenager when she had it in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on New York stage in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
While there he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001 he titled his memoir “Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life”.
“I didn't put anything there that I thought would hurt anyone or affect them in any way,” he told The Associated Press at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became a promoter of organ donation and volunteered at a hospital to assist fearful patients.
“I advise them, I give them courage, I meet with them when they come for their surgeries, and then,” he said in 1996.
I try to offer some comfort, such as “don't be afraid, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but they'll be fine.”
She was also an activist against smoking and participated in several campaigns.
They start a course that explores the “End of the World”
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clung to as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called “Deudarmageddon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian end time theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever,” Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If you analyze what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mind.
And he is not the only teacher offering courses on the “end of the world” this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, adjunct professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course “Media, Culture and the End of the World”.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We look at why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students analyzed movies with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare with real life examples.
“I've tried to inform students about what's possible, probable, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, entitled only “The End of the World”.
“We didn't add '2012' so we always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end,” Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin”, students must study, create projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work “until the very night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses proved quite popular.
“It was saturated in two hours,” Restall said of his course for high-GPA students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to console themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
The fact is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or of the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student studying Psychology and Nursing, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I've never heard of a class that could teach that,” she said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed - let alone a teacher - said they believed in the expiration date of December 21.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and we kind of discredited it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old Temple senior from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he added that there is apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, which dates back several centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise in these speculations.
“Elsewhere people don't think about this,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any courses on the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, “people will immediately start thinking about the next date” or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said that they plan to go to “end of the world” parties.
“Maybe I'll call some friends so we can have a laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
